What is up Devs üëã?‚†Ä
This program displays the expanded form of a binomial raised to a given power üî•. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
A binomial is an algebraic expression of the sum or the difference of two terms. The binomial theoram explains the expansion of a  binomial raised to a certain power. The highest power of the binomial that can be expanded using this program is 33. Any larger power will give coefficients which are larger than the maximum value that can be stored by an integer variable. It will lead to displaying incorrect coefficients. We can overcome this limitation by using classes like BigInteger from the API. 

P.S:
The str.replaceAll(String1,String2) method will replace the parts of the string str which match to String1 with String2.

If you are using a java version pior to java 18, in order to print exponents you will have to enable the support for UTF - 8 . You can enable it by setting a new environment variable called JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS to
" -Dfile.encoding=UTF-8 "
‚†Ä

node.text:
What is up Devs üëã?
This post is all about the Pascal's triangle. A Pascal's triangle is a triangular arrangement of numbers where a selected row gives the coefficients in the expansion of any binomial expression such as (x + y)‚Åø where n represents the row number if row count starts from zero. The triangle was forwarded by the mathematician Blaise Pascal in the 17th century. Although other mathematicians in Persia and China had independently discovered the triangle in the 11th century, most of the properties and applications of the triangle were discovered by Pascal. 

Some Properties of Pascal‚Äôs Triangle
‚Ä¢ Each number is the sum of the two numbers above it.
‚Ä¢ The outside numbers are all 1.
‚Ä¢ The triangle is symmetric.
‚Ä¢ The sums of the rows give the powers of 2.
‚Ä¢ Each row gives the digits of the powers of 11.
‚Ä¢ Values represent the ‚Äúbinomial coefficients ‚Äù
‚Ä¢ The Fibonacci numbers are there along diagonals 

The values(which represents the coefficients) in a specific row can be calculated by the usual nCr notation( from the binomial theoram). This program is capable of generating correct coefficients for upto 33 rows. The limit is due to the size restriction for numbers in primitive variables. We can overcome this by using non-primitive types like BigInteger. The spacing to be kept between the numbers are calculated by the Spacing class based on the largest value in the triangle. It helps to preserve the triangular shape when printing the values. It is fascinating to see so many patterns from one simple number scheme.

Follow @java.world üåç for more. 
Thank you for the support ‚ù§.

node.text:
What is up Devs üëã? In this post we solve the tower of hanoi puzzle. The key to solving the problem is to break it down to the most fundamental steps. ‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
In order solve the puzzle in a ùê¶ùê¢ùêßùê¢ùê¶ùêÆùê¶ ùêöùê¶ùê®ùêÆùêßùê≠ ùê®ùêü ùê¶ùê®ùêØùêûùê¨ we can break down all the steps into 3 main segments as shown in the slide. Segment 1 and 3 contains multiple steps, don't worry on what those steps are just yet, assume a function will do this for us.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
Now consider step 1. To transfer those set of rings consider it as a new tower with n-1 rings. The previous aux peg now being the destination and the previous destination peg now being the aux peg and apply the 3 steps again to those set of rings. This process can repeat until we consider only ‚Å£‚Å£
1 ring which is the fundamental condition. As you can see this is a recursive approach to solve the problem and also the simplest in my opinion. ‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
Now there are several other methods to solve this like using iteration , Binary and Gray code which i will not go into detail in this post.‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
This post shows the recursive approach to solve the problem. It is also important to note the approach taken to solve the problem. We broke down a larger problem into a set of smaller problems and solved it recursively. This technique is called divide and quonqer which is an important concept on the topic of thinking like a programmer. ‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
Since it will be cool if we could see these steps visually the method printTowers() in class Towers was created. Have a look at how the program solves a 10 disk tower which takes 1023 steps to solve! ‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
The minimum number of steps to solve n disks is 2‚Åø-1 and this expression can be deduced by generalisation. ‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
Time complexity: O(2‚Åø) ‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
Fun fact shown in the last slide. The graph shows the nature of a Sierpi≈Ñski triangle ( this is the triangle we saw when generating the pascals triangle and replacing the odd and even numbers with 2 different colours )‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
This is one of those problems that you should definitely try out by yourself. It will help you re-enforce the concept of recursion.‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
Share this with your friends as well.‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
As always thank you for the support.‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
Happy coding!‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£

Year end post. This one is about implementing the queue data structure as a linked list.

Here a Node class was created. Each node object will store a value and the reference to the next node. The final node will store null as the next reference. 

Advantage of this method over the previously mentioned method of using arrays is that the size of the queue is very flexible.

Enqueue complexity - O(1)
Dequeue complexity - O(1)

Try it by yourself. You'll soon get the hang of it. 
.
.

node.text:
What is up everyone üëã? This post gives a brief intro into what  the Queue data structure is and a couple of methods to implement it using an array.

The queue works with the principle called FIFO( First In First Out) where an element is inserted from one end called the Rear/Tail and the removal is done from the other end called the Front/Head.

This is exactly how a queue works in the real world E.g A ticket counter to buy movie tickets. People that come first will leave the queue first. 

The process of adding a element to the queue is known as Enqueue and removing is called Dequeue.

Queue1 shows a simple queue that will reorganise the elements with each removal of an element. Queue2 shows a simple queue that does not reorganise. Hence the size of the queue reduces with each Dequeue operation which is a drawback in that approach. The reason I used the term simple is because there exits circular, priority and double ended queues which I plan to discuss later.

An example application of the queue is handling interrupts in systems where interrupts are handled in the same order as they arrive.

* Complexity analysis -
Since we know the exact positions for adding and removing elements.
Enqueue : O(1)
Dequeue : O(1) 

Edit - Dequeue complexity in Queue1 is O(n)

Similar to the Stack a queue can be implemented as a linked list as well. That will be next.

Till then, happy coding 
.
Thank you for the support
.
.
.
.

node.text:
Hello Everyone üëã 
The last two posts showed 2  methods to implement the stack data structure. One using arrays and the other using objects as a linked list. Now it is not needed to hard code a stack from scratch since the java API(libraries i.e pre-built classes) provides a Stack class (this resides inside the java.util package) which can be used to create a stack. This post shows how you can use this class. 

Stack provides mainly 5 methods push(E item) , pop() , peek()üëÄ , empty(), search(Object o)üîé. 

There are other methods inherited by the Stack class from it's parents. You can have a comprehensive look into all the methods through java api docs. docs.oracle.com/javase/10/docs/api/java/util/stack.html

P.S: If you are wondering how printing the Stack variable prints all the elements in the stack this is how. Any java class implicitly extends a class named object. There is a method named toString() which is inherited by any java object and is responsible for determining the content that is shown when we print the variable of the object. The default content shown is the address of the object. But we can override this method to show otherwise. This is what has been done inside the Stack class to show its elements. More on inheritance and overriding later. Exciting stuff. Can't wait to post on those topics

Code by @_binath_

What is up Devs üëã?‚Å£
This post shows the stack data structure implemented by chaining objects üîó üìö. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Each object is known as a node and each of these Node objects store the reference to another node which stores the previously entered data value. When using an array to implement a stack , it is required to declare the size of it beforehand (if you missed my previous post by any chance have a look at it where I explained the functioning of the stack with the help of arrays). In this method a size declaration as such is not required. But a size limit can be implemented in the code if required. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Variable 'top' stores the reference to the object which contains the last entered data value. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Time Complexity: O(n)
Space complexity: O(n)

Got any questions regarding the code or the logic behind it ? feel free to ask them in the comments section below. ‚Å£

What is up Devsüëã ? This post explains the functioning of the "stack" data structure.

A data structure provides a format for organizing, processing, retrieving and storing data. When used appropriately they help improve the efficiency of handling data.

 A stack works just like a stack of plates except here we use data instead of plates. We add plates to the top and remove plates from the top. The last plate to get on the stack is the first to go out. To get to a plate on the bottom you first have to remove the plates above it. So the principle of this structure is called LIFO( Last In First Out ).

In this example I have used a java array to show the working of a stack. The maximum allowed size of the stack is determined at the point of creating the stack. But remember that the size of it at any given time is determined by the number of data that have been added into the stack. This size will be less than or equal to the maximum allowed size. Push and Pop are the standard names of the methods used to add and remove data.

Space complexity( for n push operations) O(n)
Time complexity to create the stack O(1)
Time complexity to push and pop O(1)

One instance where the stack is used is in memory to store data regarding method calls. This stack is known as the method call stack. This allows us to have nested methods and recursion. 

Another way to implement the stack is to link objects called nodes one after the other. Also there is a Stack class in the API which puts out the need to write a stack by ourselves. I wish to post on those as well.
Play around with this data structure and you'll soon get the hang of it.

What is up Devsüëã?
This post is about text blocks üßä. This feature was introduced to help reduce the syntax used to build up a string which spans multiple lines. This is done by eliminating the need to specify a lot of line breaks, string concatenations and quotation marks.This improves code clarity as well ( as shown in class TextBlocks1 by comparing string s1 and s2). Text blocks enable us to easily embed code snippets and texts as it is. 

It is important to remember that text blocks is just an alternative form of string representation and can be used to replace a traditional double quoted string at any time. Meaning that it can be used along with other strings in concatenation or can be passed into a method which accepts a string as well as application of string methods and string formatting. String methods and formatting will be a topic for another post. 

P.S: The reason why there needs to be a line break after the opening delimiter """ is to avoid the problem of having to change the indentation of the entire text block when needed to change the indentation of the surrounding code.
.
Feature availability: preview in java 13 & 14. Made permanent from java 15.

This post is about local variable type inference. This is a feature introduced in Java 10 that¬†allows the developer to skip the type declaration associated with local variables by using the 'var' keyword. Variable type inference refers to the ability of the compiler to automatically determine the type of a variable. Whenever the type cannot be determined it will throw an error.  The purpose for using it is purely to help shorten commands and improve readability.‚Å£
‚Å£
Key terms mentioned in the code: ‚Å£
‚Å£
Type safe- The compiler will validate types while compiling, and throw an error if you try to assign the wrong type to a variable. Variables will always belong to some type.‚Å£
‚Å£
Backward compatibility - The ability to support code written in a previous version.‚Å£
E.g- Even if var was used as a variable name in a java code written for a previous version, it will still compile ‚úÖ.‚Å£
